Thanks to D2K, I got similar idea (but well got busy these last days).Simpler rules to simpler system.

  • Someone number his questions, as QX.
  • And another will answer that question with AX.
  • If the answer isn't enough satisfying, repeat your question as QXbis/ter, add an answer with AXbis/ter, or even QX.Y/AX.Y etc.

Example:
player1Q13. ?player2A13. .player1Q13a or Q13bis or Q13.1. ?player3A13a or A13bis or A13.1.

This is a thread for helping each other on short questions that shouldn't need multiple answers nor debate. If you want to debate, create a new topic for.

I know some of you love to argue with each other, but wisely enough, you can fence words with your own mailboxes.

A19. Strategy. What does this actually do?
On june 30, 2013
BlackAndLoki

Avaquen you should write Q19 (Question) or you will be warned by our brave moderators.

A 19
Theoretically: without Strategy, the dinoz attacks first with the strongest assault compared to the other assaults.

With Strategy, it attacks first with the strongest assault compared to the enemy defenses, even if that assault is not the strongest compared to the others. For the next assault it attacks with the second strongest assault, and so on

The Strategy skill does not choose target for your dino, so it works without problem with analyze, without mercy and concentration.

F.e
Dinoz A:
Assaults
45, 12, 15, 11, 2

Dinoz B
Defenses:
20, 10, 32, 21, 5

Attacks order of dinoz A vs dinoz B with Strategy:

Attacks order without Strategy:

Now why theoretically, I have feeling it doesn't work as it should for now.

As example I've tested today 2 of my dinoz
Mouffe with strategy and such assaults:
119 42 37 27 17

vs casti with defences:
42 45 41 42 36

With and without strategy (all other skills were switched off) attacks order of Mouffe was:

And it is definitely not cool cause it should be with strategy.

So strategy seems to be bugged. Anyway you can simple hold it turned off in pvp cause it doesn't give you big advantages and in pvm it has no big influence also.

R21

PvP epic rewards didn't count, though PvE did (but not the one through contest). There's 24 categories to find points:

How many times your dinoz died, defended, attacked, moved, killed (monsters and dinoz are two different categories), gained a level, gained a level in one exact element (five categories), healed, reached the beauty contest finals?
How many times you did searched, gathered, hunted, fished, excavated?
How many times you sold to the market, bought from the shop, moved from clan to clan?
How many days you played?

[1910516]

Q100 what is the difference between ethereal and vaporous form?
On october 31, 2013
Loppermann

A100
Ethereal form: the dinoz starts with the status "immaterial" and keeps it until it is hit by an air attack or a dinoz with perception
Vaporous form: the dinoz triggers the status "immaterial" sometimes when it is attacked and the status goes away after a short amount of time if the dinoz is not attacked by an air attack or dinoz with perception
On november 2, 2013
[895738]

A100: To elaborate on Loppermann's answer.

Ethereal form is incredible in pve as barely any monsters can break the immaterial. You won't lose any HP in pve unless you fight monsters that deal contact damage, like eeloz and kaktuz. However, you have to grab about 3 speed debuff skills to get it. It is not recommended for pvp combat.

Vaporous form lasts about 2 battle turns (around after your vaporous form dinoz uses 2 of its attacks unless it is vined). Highly recommended for pvp and pve combat because it has reasonable trigger rate and it saves you lots of damage, except contact damage.

NB: If your dinoz with either of those skills dodges an enemy dino using an air assault or perception, the immaterial is still broken.

[896143]

How does Berserk work? Does it double all your elements attack, including your weak elements so that you do 2 damage instead of 1? Is it 20 damage instead of 10 with Force Control? Is it a good skill?
On november 27, 2013
Phoenix

A117
It doubles the assault power. So the dinoz will deal more damage with it's main assaults but propbably won't deal more then 1 damage with it's inferior ones.

With Force Control if an assault damage is above 10 then Force Control has no effect if below 10 it will be 10 because of FC.

With both skills the dinoz will deal 10 damage if the doubled assault power is still not enough to deal 10+ damage with that assault.

I hope it's understandable.

Clarification (I hope):
The actual damage always depends on the attacker's assault power and the defender's defense for that element. If the assault power is less than the defense the assault deals 1 damage (10 with FC) if above than we don't know the formula for the damage, but if it's not 10 then with FC it will be 10. If the damage with the doubled assault power is more than 10 than FC has no effect.

Phoenix

A178
The Relaxative Pill adds only 50% speed bonus. But it still makes the dinoz faster even if it has speed penalty.

A dinoz with Giant has 20% penalty on it's speed which means his speed is multiplied by 0.8. If this dinoz gets a Relaxative Pill and has no other speed bonuses the speed is multiplied by 1.5 so the final speed is calculated this way: 1*0.8*1.5=1.2

Loxagon

A327: A lot of what was said here about XP is correct. At low levels you usually get reduced XP when fighting the same opponents in a group of 2 or 3 compared to fighting solo, but especially with a group of 3 you will usually meet more opponents and thereby get more XP per move/turn.

On level 1 you will meet 1 Smashroom no matter if you move with a group of 1, 2 or 3 dinos. 1 dino will get 50 base XP for that, 2 or 3 dinos 37 base XP per dino. So best move solo until you level up.

From level 2 on you should group 3 dinos as they will meet more opponents and usually level up faster that way. A group of 2 dinos rarely meets more opponents than a single dino, but still suffers from XP reduction compared to the single dino.

Because of that for grouping above level 2 the preference is 3>1>2.

(Actually grouping 4 and maybe 5 gives more XP per dino than 3 in certain circumstances later on in the game.)

On july 31, 2014
Loxagon

A289: belated answer. Group 3 dinos as soon as you reach level 2. Xp boost or not, from level 2 on it is best to use a group of 3.
Going into detail:

On level 2 you will usually meet 1 smashroom with a single dino that gives 36 base XP. To reach 107 XP for level 3 you will need to do 3 fights. There is also a very slim chance to meet a wolf on level 2 and I don't know how much XP that gives (yet), but I don't think it will give you enough XP to level up in 2 moves even if you hit that chance twice which is very unlikely.

On the other hand a group of 3 dinos will usually either meet 1 wolf & 1 smashroom for 56 base XP for every dino, or 2 smashrooms for 53 base XP for every dino. For that reason you will level up after 2 moves except if you have bad luck and meet 2 smashrooms 2 times in a row AND have no prof bonus on your account.

You see, even if you are unlucky with a group of 3 and need 3 moves it is as good as moving solo, not even speaking about the lesser HP loss a group usually has.
